<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910807-0082</DOCNO><DOCID>910807-0082.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   A Handbag of Sexism</HL><DATE>08/07/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11</SO><LP>   It's always good to see an editorial complimentary ofMargaret Thatcher (&quot;Saving a Nation,&quot; July 3), but why is itthat even when a piece praises her policies, the writercannot resist inserting the odd sexist remark, in a way thatsimply wouldn't apply if writing about a man?   For instance, &quot;the stern schoolmarm of the House ofCommons&quot; -- if it were a man, it would surely be &quot;the sternleader.&quot; And why in heaven's name is her handbag &quot;menacing&quot;?Does the writer really mean to imply there was a latentthreat to club someone with it?</LP><TEXT>   And why the backhanded compliment of &quot;potency&quot; (amasculine attribute)? Why not simply &quot;strength&quot;?   V. Benson Hanzel   Kentfield, Calif.</TEXT></DOC>